<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Memorandum – December 9, 2013</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Nongovernmental International Panel on Climate Change (IPC0042)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As senior editors and lead authors for the Nongovernmental International Panel on Climate Change (NIIPCC), we are pleased to provide you with brief comments questions asked in your “Select Committee Announcement 31.” </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These matters are discussed in greate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r detail in three books, a Summary for Policymakers, and a policy brief we coauthored since 2009: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Climate Change Reconsidered</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Idso and Singer, 2009), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Climate Change Reconsidered: 2011 Interim Report</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Idso, Carter, and Singer, 2011), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Climate Change Reconsi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">dered II: Physical Science</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Idso, Carter, and Singer, 2013a), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Summary for Policymakers – CCRII </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(Idso, Carter, and Singer, 2013b), and “Scientific Critique of the IPCC’s 2013 Summary for Policymakers” (Idso, Carter, Singer, and Soon, 2013), all available on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">line at www.climatechangereconsidered.org or in printed form from The Heartland Institute, One South Wacker Drive Suite 2740, Chicago, Illinois 60606 USA.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Qualifications</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Nongovernmental International Panel on Climate Change, or NIPCC, is an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">international panel of scientists and scholars who came together to understand the causes and consequences of climate change. NIPCC has no formal attachment to or sponsorship from any government or governmental agency. It is wholly independent of political</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> pressures and influences and therefore is not predisposed to produce politically motivated conclusions or policy recommendations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In September 2013 – two weeks prior to the release of the fifth assessment report (AR5) of the United Nations’ International</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) – NIPCC released </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Climate Change Reconsidered II: Physical Science, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the fourth in its series of alternative reports to the alarmist reports of the IPCC. Nearly 50 scientists from 15 countries participated as authors, contribu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tors, or reviewers, of the 1,000-page peer-reviewed report.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A fifth volume in the series, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Climate Change Reconsidered II</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">: Impacts, Adaptation, and Vulnerability</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, is planned for release in 2014.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How robust are the conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Basis report?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The conclusions are not robust.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Although the IPCC’s reports are voluminous and their arguments persistent, the claims of rising confidence in attributing effects to human greenhouse gas emissions and predictions of future warming and climate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> change are not supported by scientific </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In order to conduct a proper scientific investigation, scientists must first formulate a falsifiable hypothesis to test. An alternative and null hypothesis – the simplest hypothesis consistent with the known facts – must be entertained. The hypothesis impl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">icit though rarely explicitly stated in the IPCC’s work is that dangerous global warming is resulting, or will result, from human-related greenhouse gas emissions. The null hypothesis is that currently observed changes are the result of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">natural variability</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">To invalidate the null hypothesis requires, at a minimum, direct evidence of human causation of specified changes that lie outside usual, natural variability.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> The IPCC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">failed to meet this burden of proof.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It relies on global climate models that can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not rule out natural variability as the cause of observed climate changes, postulates that assume the truth of the hypothesis they should be testing, and circumstantial evidence that does not bear directly on the matters in dispute and therefore cannot con</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">stitute proof of a human impact on climate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Have [</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">sic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">] the IPCC adequately addressed criticisms of previous reports?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">No it has not. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">NIPCC in 2009 and again in 2011 produced detailed reports (cited above) summarizing thousands of peer-reviewed studies </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that contradicted the IPCC’s Fourth Assessment Report. Scores of books by qualified authors have exposed the bias and inaccuracies of past IPCC reports, yet the latest report ignores them and repeats the same errors.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The research reviews appearing in NIPC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">C’s 2013 report (also cited above) were posted online at www.nipccreport.org as they were written between 2011 and 2013, making them available for review and consideration by the IPCC. Attention to those findings would have forced the IPCC to conclude that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> confidence in its computer models and postulates has fallen, not increased, over time.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How much scope is there to question the report’s conclusions? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The report’s conclusions should be vigorously criticized. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dr. Richard Lindzen, emeritus Alfred P. Sloan Professor of Meteorology, Department of Earth, Atmospheric and Planetary Sciences at MIT and one of the world’s most distinguished physicists, says “I think that the latest IPCC report has truly sunk to level o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">f hilarious incoherence. They are proclaiming increased confidence in their models as the discrepancies between their models and observations increase” (Morano, 2013). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Similarly, Dr. Judith Curry, Professor and Chair of the School of Earth and Atmospheri</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c Sciences at the Georgia Institute of Technology, said “after several decades and expenditures in the bazillions, the IPCC still has not provided a convincing argument for how much warming in the 20th century has been caused by humans” (Curry, 2013).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> lead authors of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Climate Change Reconsidered II: Physical Science</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> found the IPCC has retreated from at least 11 claims promulgated in AR4 and previous reports or by scientists prominently associated with the IPCC  (Idso, Carter, Singer, and Soon, 2013). We</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> found the AR5 Summary for Policymakers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">contains at least 13 misleading or untrue statements and 11 statements phrased in such a way that they mislead readers or misrepresent important aspects of the science (Ibid.).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent does AR5 reflect </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the range of views among climate scientists? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Very poorly, if at all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The NIPCC was formed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">because </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the IPCC does not accept advice from scientists who are critical of its mode of operation or main conclusions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is ample evidence of dissent from what</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the IPCC claims is “scientific consensus.” </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Climate Change Reconsidered II: Physical Science </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">quotes directly from nearly 4,000 peer-reviewed articles that undermine or contradict important parts of the IPCC’s positions. The IPCC ignores, minimizes, or misi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nterprets this vast body of research.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">More than 30,000 American scientists signed the Oregon Petition stating there is no “no convincing evidence” carbon dioxide is dangerously warming the planet or disrupting its climate. A 114-page directory of the actual names of signers, sorted by state of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> residence, appears in an appendix to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Climate Change Reconsidered</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Most climate scientists say we do not know enough about climate processes and lack the accurate data necessary to build reliable global climate models, even though they profess to “believe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">” in man-made global warming (Bray and von Storch, 2010; Bast, 2010). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A survey of professional meteorologists and other atmospheric science experts conducted in 2012 by the American Meteorological Society (AMS) found only 52 percent said they believe glo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">bal warming is happening and is mostly human-caused. Even fewer believe, as the IPCC’s authors do, that such warming would be dangerous (Stenhouse </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 2013; Bast 2013a).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Surveys and abstract-counting exercises that claim to find evidence for consensus </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">either ask the wrong questions – e.g., they fail to ask if global warming is man-made or large enough to constitute a real threat – or are plagued by methodological problems (Legates et al., 2013).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Can any of the areas of the science now be considered se</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ttled as a result of AR5’s publication, if so which? What areas need further effort to reduce the levels of uncertainty? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Few if any areas of climate science can be considered “settled.”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Climate change research is a relatively new and immature scientific </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">subdiscipline. Many of its current practitioners have allowed their views to be influenced by political rather than exclusively scientific considerations. In consequence, and despite the sound elemental physics, chemistry, and geology involved, there is no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> certainty regarding the most important matter under consideration, the degree to which human carbon dioxide emissions may or may not be causing significant global warming.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effective is AR5 and the summary for policymakers in conveying what is meant by uncertainty in scientific terms? Would a focus on risk rather than uncertainty be useful? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The AR5 allocates spurious probability estimates to its conclusions in an attemp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">t to portray a scientific rigor that is actually absent. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is wholly unscientific, and such claims should play no role in informing public policy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The IPCC’s use of “probability” terminology is not based on rigorous statistical trials or numerical anal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ysis, as is normally used to derive statistically meaningful confidence intervals. Instead, IPCC’s quasi-numeric confidence statements represent considered “expert opinion,” </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reflecting a process not very different from a show of hands around a discussion t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">able. The terminology confers an impression of scientific rectitude onto a process that is inescapably subjective.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Does AR5 address the reliability of climate models?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">AR5 admits climate models are less reliable than it previously claimed, but still defe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nds them. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The June draft of the AR5 SPM contained the statement that “Models do not generally reproduce the observed reduction in surface warming trend over the last 10-15 years” (Section D-1, Draft SPM-10), but this statement was removed from the final, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">published version of the SPM.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The published version of the AR5 SPM says “There are ... differences between simulated and observed trends over periods as short as 10 to 15 years (e.g., 1998 to 2012)” (SPM-10); “there remains low confidence in the representation and quantification of [cl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oud and aerosol) processes in models” (SPM-11); and “most models simulate a small downward trend in Antarctic sea ice extent, albeit with larger inter-model spread, in contrast to the small upward trend in observations” (SPM-11). These are major concession</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s to long-time critics of the IPCC’s over-reliance on global climate models. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The IPCC doesn’t go far enough in criticizing its models. Internal climate oscillations (AMO, PDO, etc.) are major features of the historic temperature record; climate models do</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> not even attempt to simulate them. Similarly, climate models fail to incorporate the effects of variations in solar magnetic field or in the flux of cosmic rays, both of which are known to significantly affect climate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Climate models project an ocean </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">warming of at least 0.2°C since 2000; in fact, no warming is observed. Climate models project the appearance of an upper troposphere hot-spot in tropical regions; none is observed.  Climate models project late twentieth century warming should have occurred</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> towards both poles; in fact, warming was confined to north polar regions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Climate models underestimate surface evaporation caused by increased temperature by a factor of three, resulting in a consequential underestimation of global precipitation. Climate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> models represent aerosol-induced changes in infrared (IR) radiation inadequately, despite studies showing different mineral aerosols (for equal loadings) can cause differences in surface IR flux between 7 and 25 Wm</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">-2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Has AR5 sufficiently explained the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">reasons behind the widely reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">No it has not.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The IPCC offers two alternative explanations for the termination of the late-twentieth century warming phase: that the now-prolonged period of temperature </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">stasis reflects a statistical fluctuation; or, alternatively, that the cessation of warming has been caused by the accumulation of heat in the deep ocean (AR5 SPM, p. 10).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The IPCC clearly remains ambivalent about which, if either, of these two </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">explanations is correct. It fails to explain how heat can be transferred to the deep ocean without first passing through the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">shallow ocean, which has not warmed since at least 2003 (Pielke, 2008).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The lack of warming for the past 15 to 17 years (depending</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on how the trend is calculated) poses a major challenge to the claim that man-made carbon dioxide emissions are driving climate change. Atmospheric concentration of carbon dioxide rose 8 percent in the past 16 years, an amount equal to 34 percent of all C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">O2 added to the atmosphere since the start of the industrial revolution. If this rise didn’t cause a concurrent increase in climate temperatures, then other </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">natural </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">forcings and feedbacks must be greater than or operating in the opposite direction from wha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t the hypothesis assumes. There is no reason, therefore, to trust climate models that forecast future warming.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do the AR5 Physical Science Basis report’s conclusions strengthen or weaken the economic case for action to prevent dangerous climate change? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It weakens </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">what was already a weak </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">case for action.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> AR5 now admits there has been little or no warming in the past 15 years, that its computer models failed to predict this pause, and that it has “‘Low confidence’ that damaging increases will occur in eit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">her drought or tropical cyclone activity” (AR5 SPM, p. 23). Neither previous nor the current draft IPCC reports contain evidence that justifies the implementation of public policy aimed at cutting human carbon dioxide emissions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What implications do the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">IPCC’s conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report have for policy making both nationally and internationally? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">By failing to provide evidence that suggests that dangerous global warming (or any measurable warming, for that matter) is caused by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">human emissions, AR5 provides no basis for active policy measures to limit carbon dioxide emissions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Between 1988 and 2001 (the span of preparation of its first three Assessment Reports), the IPCC was the sole international body providing advice to govern</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ments on the global warming issue. With the formation of the Nongovernmental Panel on Climate Change (NIPCC) in 2003, a second and independent team of scientific assessors emerged.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">NIPCC finds “the IPCC has exaggerated the amount of warming likely to occur if the concentration of atmospheric CO2 were to double, and such warming as occurs is likely to be modest and cause no net harm to the global environment or to human well-being” (I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">dso, Carter, Singer, 2013b). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The IPCC’s “Green Team” scientific advice can be weighed against the views of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the NIPCC’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“Red Team” of independent scholars. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Policymakers have a responsibility to be fully familiar with the arguments and conclusions of both </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">teams.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is the IPCC process an effective mechanism for assessing scientific knowledge? Or has it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">focused</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> on providing a justification for political commitment? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The IPCC has failed to investigate climate change “in the round” and has focused exclusively </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">on matters to do with human greenhouse gas emissions. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This has caused IPCC to fail to involve truly independent scientists in its deliberations, with the result that its conclusions are biased and of little value for policy formulation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The United Nations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> protocol under which the IPCC operates specifically defines climate change as “a change of climate which is attributed directly or indirectly to human activity that alters the composition of the global atmosphere and which is in addition to natural climat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e variability observed over comparable time periods” (United Nations, 1994, Article 1.2). Not surprisingly, directing attention to only the effects of human greenhouse gas emissions has resulted in the IPCC failing to provide a thorough analysis of climate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> change. (Idso </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, 2013b)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Nature, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the prestigious science journal that has long pressed for global action on global warming, nevertheless editorialized that “the IPCC’s mega-assessments are out of date by the time they hit the streets” and “it is time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to rethink the IPCC. The organization deserves thanks and respect from all who care about the principle of evidence-based policy-making, but the current report should be its last mega-assessment” (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Nature, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2013).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Judith Curry, previously cited, says “The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">IPCC needs to get out of the way so that scientists and policy makers can better do their jobs”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(Curry 2013). The scientists of NIPCC agree.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">REFERENCES</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New 